    ],
    "map_entry": "Historical overview of light speed measurement and Einstein's theories, with practical impacts such as GPS.",
    "summary": "The text recounts how the speed of light was first measured by Fizeau and Fresnel in 1840‑45, how it led to Einstein’s thought experiments, and ultimately his special and general relativity. It highlights key experiments such as Michelson–Morley (1901), which failed to detect ether, prompting a shift from Galilean to Lorentzian physics. The narrative explains how relativity made time relative, introduced length contraction, and linked space and gravity in spacetime. Practical consequences like GPS satellite timing corrections are noted. Overall, it offers a concise historical lesson on how empirical data reshaped our understanding of light, motion, and the fabric of the universe.",
    "review_path": "Review/Upending Our Understanding of the Universe.review.md",
    "processed_path": "Processed/Upending Our Understanding of the Universe.md",
